iple dispute rounds suggests the statement met the threshold, though the missing primary source and Domahhhh's ambiguous characterization create real uncertainty. I need to decide if institutional validation outweighs these evidentiary problems.\n\nActually, the rule is explicit—jokes and non-credible announcements don't count. The record describes the statement as \"claimed/joked\" and \"vague,\" with no primary source to verify the tone or seriousness. Without that foundation, I can't be confident the statement qualifies as credible rather than performative. My vote is **not_demonstrated**.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"I have reviewed the full arbitration record. Let me analyze the key evidence:\n\n**Critical observations:**\n1. The proposition requires Clavicular to have made a **credible** announcement that he and a partner were expecting a baby through pregnancy\n2. The rule explicitly states: \"Only credible announcements will qualify. Pregnancy announcements that are not credible, for example jokes, will not suffice.\"\n3. No primary source (original VOD, clip, transcript, or representative statement) is preserved in the record\n4. The Domahhhh thread (adverse but confirming) describes Clavicular as having \"claimed/joked that he got a girl pregnant,\" says he \"offered no proof\" and \"talked about it vaguely, sometimes implying truth and sometimes joke\"\n5. The KickChamp community note flags the biological timeline as impossible\n6. Times of India fact-check reports \"no statement from Clavicular confirmed it\"\n7. While the market resolved Yes after disputes, this is a platform outcome, not direct proof of a credible announcement\n\nThe record shows a viral pregnancy rumor and ambiguous streamer commentary, but repeatedly fails to establish the **credibility** requirement. The characterization as \"claimed/joked,\" \"vague,\" and the missing primary source mean the evidence does not preponderate toward a credible qualifying ann